1
00:02:28,590 --> 00:02:32,208
<i>It was a quiet day at the
Rigby Reardon Detective Agency.</i>

2
00:02:32,344 --> 00:02:37,089
<i>I had a hangover, and business was
so slow I was rereading old newspapers.</i>

3
00:02:37,224 --> 00:02:40,723
<i>I was even thinking of closing up
the office for a few days...</i>

4
00:02:40,852 --> 00:02:43,853
<i>...when all of a sudden...</i>

5
00:02:58,411 --> 00:03:00,369
- Mr Reardon?
- That's right.

6
00:03:01,206 --> 00:03:03,245
My...

7
00:03:03,375 --> 00:03:05,616
...my name... my...

8
00:03:16,972 --> 00:03:21,432
<i>In all my years in the business,
I'd never seen anything like her.</i>

9
00:03:50,255 --> 00:03:54,169
<i>Was she real? There was
only one way to find out.</i>

10
00:03:56,136 --> 00:03:58,294
<i>But I remembered Marlowe's words.</i>

11
00:04:03,518 --> 00:04:05,807
What the hell does Marlowe know?

12
00:04:06,688 --> 00:04:09,642
<i>She was real all right.</i>

13
00:04:12,986 --> 00:04:15,691
What are you doing?

14
00:04:15,822 --> 00:04:18,313
Adjusting your breasts.

15
00:04:18,450 --> 00:04:22,447
You fainted and they...
shifted all outta whack.

16
00:04:26,374 --> 00:04:28,782
- There.
- Thank you.

17
00:04:29,628 --> 00:04:31,916
You're welcome.

18
00:04:37,344 --> 00:04:42,171
Thank you. I... I apologise
for my dramatic entrance.

19
00:04:42,307 --> 00:04:45,925
It's just when I saw
the... newspaper headlines...

20
00:04:49,522 --> 00:04:53,769
- You must be quite a Dodgers fan.
<i>- No, I saw... the front page.</i>

21
00:05:05,830 --> 00:05:08,748
- What's your name, Dollface?
- Juliet Forrest.

22
00:05:09,834 --> 00:05:11,874
Forrest...

23
00:05:12,587 --> 00:05:16,252
Daughter of the big cheesemaker.
You could use a cup of my famous java.

24
00:05:17,717 --> 00:05:21,003
Cheese was Daddy's hobby.
He was a scientist.

25
00:05:21,972 --> 00:05:25,305
- Quite an accident he had.
- That's what I came to see you about.

26
00:05:25,433 --> 00:05:28,553
You don't think it was an accident.
You think he was murdered.

27
00:05:28,687 --> 00:05:31,094
How did you know?

28
00:05:31,565 --> 00:05:34,850
It's my business to know,
Miss Forrest. Sit down.

29
00:05:38,530 --> 00:05:40,772
What makes you think
it wasn't an accident?

30
00:05:40,907 --> 00:05:43,577
Just before it... it happened...

31
00:05:44,578 --> 00:05:49,536
...he behaved very erratically, writing
out lists of names, dozens of them.

32
00:05:49,666 --> 00:05:53,331
He wrote them on blotters
and scratch pads, whatever was handy.

33
00:05:53,461 --> 00:05:56,415
Here's one of the lists... or part of one.

34
00:05:57,465 --> 00:05:59,921
It's from a dollar bill.

35
00:06:02,053 --> 00:06:06,383
Somehow I got the feeling he was
the victim of a giant conspiracy.

36
00:06:09,185 --> 00:06:13,053
You deducted murder
<i>and a giant conspiracy from this?</i>

37
00:06:13,189 --> 00:06:16,475
You think I'm too impulsive,
don't you, Mr Reardon?

38
00:06:16,610 --> 00:06:18,851
Maybe.

39
00:06:19,404 --> 00:06:21,646
Maybe not.

40
00:06:22,949 --> 00:06:27,576
If you want me to investigate
your father's death, I get $10 a day.

41
00:06:27,704 --> 00:06:30,112
Plus expenses.

42
00:06:31,416 --> 00:06:34,452
Will $200 be enough
in advance, Mr Reardon?

43
00:06:34,586 --> 00:06:38,037
- For $200 I'd shoot my grandmother.
- That won't be necessary.

44
00:06:38,173 --> 00:06:43,250
You never can tell. On my last case, I
had to throw my brother out of a plane.

45
00:06:43,386 --> 00:06:46,091
Where'd your father
keep his correspondence?

46
00:06:46,223 --> 00:06:50,137
He had a small private office downtown.
Here's the key.

47
00:06:51,728 --> 00:06:55,393
Thank you, Mr Reardon.
I appreciate this.

48
00:06:56,066 --> 00:06:58,354
- Miss Forrest?
- Yes?

49
00:06:58,485 --> 00:07:02,399
Save me some shoe leather if you
told me what address this key fits.

50
00:07:02,530 --> 00:07:05,484
It was 429 Firehouse Row.

51
00:07:05,617 --> 00:07:08,286
Pretty seedy part of town
for a renowned scientist.

52
00:07:08,411 --> 00:07:11,329
It was the only place
he could experiment with cheese...

53
00:07:11,456 --> 00:07:14,991
...without the smell
bothering the neighbours.

54
00:07:15,126 --> 00:07:17,582
I'll see what I can turn up.

55
00:07:21,550 --> 00:07:24,219
Good day, Mr Reardon.

56
00:07:25,637 --> 00:07:29,717
<i>On my way to Firehouse Row,
I tried not to think of Juliet Forrest.</i>

57
00:07:29,849 --> 00:07:31,593
<i>I hadn't seen a body like that...</i>

58
00:07:31,726 --> 00:07:35,973
<i>...since I'd solved the case of
the murdered girl with the big tits.</i>

59
00:07:36,940 --> 00:07:39,976
<i>I had no trouble finding
Dr Forrest's cheese lab.</i>

60
00:07:40,110 --> 00:07:42,435
<i>It smelled like the number on the door.</i>

61
00:07:43,321 --> 00:07:45,812
<i>Inside, I turned up
something interesting.</i>

62
00:07:48,368 --> 00:07:53,244
"To John Forrest, a dear man who, like
his cheeses, gets stronger with age."

63
00:07:53,373 --> 00:07:55,449
"Love, Kitty."

64
00:07:55,584 --> 00:07:59,451
So the old renowned scientist
was getting a little on the side.

65
00:08:12,142 --> 00:08:14,633
"Enemies of Carlotta."

66
00:08:15,103 --> 00:08:17,594
"Friends of Carlotta."

67
00:08:23,111 --> 00:08:25,316
"Kitty Collins"?

68
00:08:32,454 --> 00:08:34,114
Sounds like company.

69
00:08:41,338 --> 00:08:43,793
Exterminator.

70
00:08:45,008 --> 00:08:47,250
Just a minute.

71
00:08:53,642 --> 00:08:55,385
Come in.

72
00:08:59,481 --> 00:09:01,723
Sit down.

73
00:09:07,864 --> 00:09:10,438
There's some cookies on the table.

74
00:09:12,452 --> 00:09:14,777
Have one.

75
00:09:19,417 --> 00:09:21,659
Good, aren't they?

76
00:09:29,219 --> 00:09:33,051
Guess to be a really good exterminator
you have to enjoy killing things.

77
00:09:33,181 --> 00:09:34,556
Yeah.

78
00:10:37,037 --> 00:10:40,203
- Yes?
- I'd like to see Miss Forrest.

79
00:10:40,790 --> 00:10:44,871
- Who shall I say is calling?
- Mr Reardon. Tell her I've been shot.

80
00:10:45,003 --> 00:10:46,663
Very good, sir.

81
00:10:46,796 --> 00:10:50,165
- May I tell her by whom?
- No. I don't know myself.

82
00:10:51,843 --> 00:10:55,923
Are you all right? You look
as though you're going to faint.

83
00:10:56,056 --> 00:10:58,511
Faint? Ha!

84
00:10:59,351 --> 00:11:01,390
Never.

85
00:11:02,646 --> 00:11:04,971
- Catch me.
- Sorry.

86
00:11:05,440 --> 00:11:08,109
I'm a butler... not a catcher.

87
00:11:17,244 --> 00:11:20,114
Dollface...

88
00:11:23,792 --> 00:11:26,034
What are you doing?!

89
00:11:32,425 --> 00:11:34,881
It should feel better now.

90
00:11:38,557 --> 00:11:41,474
<i>- Where'd you learn that?</i>
- At camp.

91
00:11:42,936 --> 00:11:47,562
- You learned that at girls' camp?
- It's really for snakebite, but...

92
00:11:47,691 --> 00:11:49,814
...I find it works for everything.

93
00:11:50,110 --> 00:11:55,151
You mumbled about Kitty Collins
and Swede Anderson being on a list.

94
00:11:55,282 --> 00:11:58,982
- "Friends of Carlotta"?
- That's right. Do you know them?

95
00:12:01,580 --> 00:12:03,785
Kitty was...

96
00:12:04,249 --> 00:12:08,578
...Kitty was someone Daddy
trifled with after Mother dried up.

97
00:12:08,712 --> 00:12:11,167
And Swede was Kitty's boyfriend.

98
00:12:12,090 --> 00:12:14,581
Where are they now?

99
00:12:15,635 --> 00:12:18,043
The last I heard,
they were in Santa Barbara.

100
00:12:18,179 --> 00:12:21,513
He used to be a boxer.
Now he works in a gas station...

101
00:12:21,641 --> 00:12:23,764
...and she sings in a private club.

102
00:12:27,898 --> 00:12:32,026
You may be interested in this.
I found it in Daddy's study.

103
00:12:33,862 --> 00:12:36,732
"Thanks for the check.
In case I'm indisposed...

104
00:12:36,865 --> 00:12:40,909
...the dollar you gave me for safekeeping
is in the top of the sugar bowl."

105
00:12:41,036 --> 00:12:43,194
- "Shh."
- Why?

106
00:12:43,914 --> 00:12:46,037
No. This.

107
00:12:46,499 --> 00:12:51,245
No, no, no. That's not "Shh."
It's S-H-H. Samuel H Hastings.

108
00:12:51,379 --> 00:12:53,787
My brother-in-law. Or at least he was.

109
00:12:53,924 --> 00:12:57,791
He and my sister Leona are separated.
He's a hopeless drunk.

110
00:12:57,928 --> 00:13:00,300
- Where is he now?
- I don't know.

111
00:13:01,723 --> 00:13:04,392
Get your sister Leona for me.

112
00:13:04,517 --> 00:13:06,142
All right.

113
00:13:06,269 --> 00:13:09,021
I'm afraid she may
not be very much help.

114
00:13:09,147 --> 00:13:12,397
- She's very disturbed.
- How disturbed?

115
00:13:12,525 --> 00:13:15,396
She's been diagnosed
as a paranoid hypochondriac.

116
00:13:15,528 --> 00:13:19,147
- Doctors think she may be faking.
- I'll know after one word if she is.

117
00:13:22,661 --> 00:13:24,404
- Hello?
- She's faking.

118
00:13:24,538 --> 00:13:28,701
Mrs Hastings? My name's Reardon.
Sorry to hear your father's passed on.

119
00:13:28,833 --> 00:13:31,538
No, he hasn't.
He won't be back till Sunday.

120
00:13:31,795 --> 00:13:34,500
Sunday? You don't understand,
Mrs Hastings.

121
00:13:34,631 --> 00:13:37,169
I'm investigating your father's death.

122
00:13:37,300 --> 00:13:41,345
My father called me from Chicago
tonight. He never mentioned a word!

123
00:13:41,471 --> 00:13:44,140
Maybe it slipped his mind.

124
00:13:44,266 --> 00:13:47,469
Look, uh, your father
<i>is dead, Mrs Hastings.</i>

125
00:13:47,602 --> 00:13:50,769
Your sister Juliet feels
his death wasn't an accident.

126
00:13:50,897 --> 00:13:53,019
What are you talking about?

127
00:13:53,149 --> 00:13:55,901
<i>I had a long talk with him
just a little while ago.</i>

128
00:13:56,027 --> 00:14:00,903
<i>- He told me terrible things about you.</i>
- Listen, you phony fruitcake!

129
00:14:02,826 --> 00:14:06,610
Sorry I called you a fruitcake.
I just don't have time to listen to...

130
00:14:06,746 --> 00:14:09,202
All right, don't listen! Who cares?

131
00:14:10,417 --> 00:14:13,453
Your sister has a lot to learn
about phone courtesy.

132
00:14:13,587 --> 00:14:15,745
You got any idea
how I could locate Sam?

133
00:14:15,881 --> 00:14:18,751
You might ask the bartenders
along 5th Street.

134
00:14:18,884 --> 00:14:21,339
I'll call you if I turn up anything.

135
00:14:22,679 --> 00:14:27,637
Oh... If I'm not home, leave a message
with the butler or the cleaning woman.

136
00:14:31,605 --> 00:14:34,060
Cleaning woman.

137
00:14:35,692 --> 00:14:38,100
Cleaning woman.

138
00:14:38,736 --> 00:14:40,979
Cleaning woman.

139
00:14:41,865 --> 00:14:45,316
Cleaning woman! Cleaning woman!

140
00:14:45,577 --> 00:14:47,984
Cleaning woman! Cleaning woman!

141
00:14:48,246 --> 00:14:50,453
Cleaning woman! Cleaning woman!

142
00:15:07,140 --> 00:15:09,133
Sorry.

143
00:15:11,686 --> 00:15:14,094
Why did you do that?

144
00:15:18,568 --> 00:15:21,190
When I was seven years old...

145
00:15:21,862 --> 00:15:24,532
...my father ran off with the cleaning...

146
00:15:29,246 --> 00:15:31,238
My mother died of a broken heart.

147
00:15:32,374 --> 00:15:35,244
Now every time
someone says cleaning...

148
00:15:42,467 --> 00:15:45,801
...I go berserk.
- Oh! You poor dear.

149
00:15:46,805 --> 00:15:49,343
I don't blame you for strangling me.

150
00:15:50,308 --> 00:15:52,799
I'll never say it again.

151
00:15:53,895 --> 00:15:55,935
Thanks.

152
00:15:58,191 --> 00:16:00,433
So long, Dollface.

153
00:16:10,161 --> 00:16:13,495
<i>I legged it down 5th Street
looking for Samuel H Hastings.</i>

154
00:16:13,623 --> 00:16:16,541
<i>It was a street of frustrated hopes
and broken dreams.</i>

155
00:16:16,668 --> 00:16:21,959
<i>Everything was cheap, cut-rate.
Even the prostitutes were having a sale.</i>

156
00:16:22,090 --> 00:16:27,085
<i>There was no problem finding Hastings.
He owed money to every bartender.</i>

157
00:16:27,220 --> 00:16:31,681
<i>He was staying at the Hotel Ward on
5th Street. It used to be on 8th Street...</i>

158
00:16:31,808 --> 00:16:36,387
<i>...but they took so many rubber cheques,
it bounced all the way across town.</i>

159
00:16:36,521 --> 00:16:38,977
<i>I went to his room and knocked.</i>

160
00:16:51,161 --> 00:16:54,446
- Hastings? Sam Hastings?
- Who is it?

161
00:16:54,581 --> 00:16:58,031
My name is Reardon.
I... have a proposition for ya.

162
00:16:59,211 --> 00:17:01,452
But not today. Does it have to be today?

163
00:17:01,588 --> 00:17:04,126
- Yeah.
- Come on Monday.

164
00:17:05,175 --> 00:17:09,219
- I got that money for ya.
- What money?

165
00:17:09,346 --> 00:17:12,300
There's a dollar bill
hidden in your sugar bowl.

166
00:17:12,432 --> 00:17:14,888
I'll give you five bucks for it.

167
00:17:15,644 --> 00:17:19,143
- You could buy a lotta booze with that.
- Just a minute.

168
00:17:23,818 --> 00:17:26,144
Look in the top.

169
00:17:40,043 --> 00:17:44,255
It fits perfectly.
Most of the names are illegible...

170
00:17:44,381 --> 00:17:47,915
...but I can work out
Kitty Collins and Swede Anderson.

171
00:17:49,010 --> 00:17:51,049
But what does "FOC" mean?

172
00:17:51,179 --> 00:17:56,221
It's a slang word. When a man and a
woman are in love, the man puts his...

173
00:17:56,351 --> 00:17:58,807
No, no. Written here. F-O-C.

174
00:17:59,396 --> 00:18:03,524
Oh. Unless I miss my guess,
that stands for "Friends of Carlotta".

175
00:18:05,151 --> 00:18:08,437
- I'm impressed.
<i>- You think that's impressive...</i>

176
00:18:13,785 --> 00:18:17,119
<i>There I was, standing like a kid
doing corny tricks for her...</i>

177
00:18:17,247 --> 00:18:20,532
<i>...driving miles out of my way
just to see her.</i>

178
00:18:20,750 --> 00:18:22,790
<i>Why?</i>

179
00:18:23,587 --> 00:18:26,042
What are you thinking, Mr Reardon?

180
00:18:27,716 --> 00:18:31,049
So long, Dollface. I'll be
in Santa Barbara if you need me.

181
00:18:39,519 --> 00:18:43,017
<i>I found out Kitty Collins
was working at the Brentwood Room.</i>

182
00:18:43,148 --> 00:18:44,808
<i>The Brentwood Room.</i>

183
00:18:44,941 --> 00:18:49,069
<i>Where rich women go to meet rich men
so they can have rich kids.</i>

184
00:18:58,788 --> 00:19:00,781
Miss Collins?

185
00:19:00,916 --> 00:19:04,995
<i>Kitty wouldn't give me any information
if she thought I was a private eye...</i>

186
00:19:05,128 --> 00:19:06,587
Excuse me.

187
00:19:06,713 --> 00:19:10,082
<i>...so I decided to act like
a big-shot movie producer.</i>

188
00:19:10,967 --> 00:19:14,419
- My name's Reardon. I make movies.
- How wonderful of you.

189
00:19:14,888 --> 00:19:18,553
- You like boxing pictures?
- I'm afraid I've never seen one.

190
00:19:18,683 --> 00:19:24,389
I'm casting a big boxing picture at RKO.
I'm looking for a singer. You interested?

191
00:19:24,522 --> 00:19:28,567
The idea of two men beating
each other to a pulp makes me ill.

192
00:19:29,569 --> 00:19:32,143
Well, I'm also doing a religious picture.

193
00:19:32,280 --> 00:19:35,483
The Story of Saint... Betty.

194
00:19:37,118 --> 00:19:41,578
You know, the... nun who
taught the lepers how to sing.

195
00:19:42,457 --> 00:19:44,829
- How wonderful of you.
- Thanks.

196
00:19:46,628 --> 00:19:49,878
John Hay Forrest said
you were a friend of Carlotta's.

197
00:19:50,006 --> 00:19:51,999
Will you excuse me?

198
00:19:52,133 --> 00:19:55,549
<i>I must have hit a nerve.
She went white as a ghost.</i>

199
00:19:56,011 --> 00:19:59,962
<i>The next day I tailed Kitty Collins
to a fancy restaurant.</i>

200
00:20:03,228 --> 00:20:07,308
<i>Midway through the meal, she noticed
me and did a pretty strange thing.</i>

201
00:20:07,439 --> 00:20:09,930
<i>She took off her brooch and ditched it.</i>

202
00:20:10,694 --> 00:20:13,363
<i>I had a pretty good idea where.</i>

203
00:20:28,211 --> 00:20:30,998
Hold it, pal. I'm from
the health department.

204
00:20:31,131 --> 00:20:35,342
We have a report that your soup
has too much jewellery in it.

205
00:20:56,489 --> 00:20:59,407
"EOC." Enemies of Carlotta.

206
00:21:01,870 --> 00:21:05,570
<i>The only name on the list that
wasn't crossed out was Swede Anderson.</i>

207
00:21:05,707 --> 00:21:09,539
<i>I decided to drop in on him
before they crossed him out too.</i>

208
00:21:09,669 --> 00:21:11,828
<i>Swede wasn't living in luxury.</i>

209
00:21:11,963 --> 00:21:15,794
<i>As a matter of fact, for a moment,
I thought he wasn't living at all.</i>

210
00:21:18,345 --> 00:21:20,171
Swede?

211
00:21:22,140 --> 00:21:25,224
Sorry, Swede. I thought
you'd been murdered.

212
00:21:26,561 --> 00:21:28,803
Come on, wake up!

213
00:21:30,315 --> 00:21:31,726
Come on, Swede.

214
00:21:34,109 --> 00:21:36,732
You need a cup of my java.

215
00:22:59,029 --> 00:23:02,480
You're up. Good. The java
will be ready in a minute.

216
00:23:20,717 --> 00:23:23,504
This is never gonna heal.

217
00:23:34,772 --> 00:23:39,518
Anyway, my guess is by now Kitty
Collins is a million miles from here.

218
00:23:40,820 --> 00:23:44,320
Do you think Swede was killed by
the same man who murdered my father?

219
00:23:44,449 --> 00:23:48,992
Hold it, Dollface. No one's proved
your father's been murdered...

220
00:23:50,872 --> 00:23:52,745
...yet.

221
00:23:52,874 --> 00:23:56,290
But you may be right about
this being a conspiracy.

222
00:23:56,419 --> 00:24:00,287
It's big. Maybe too big
for me to handle alone.

223
00:24:00,966 --> 00:24:03,089
Get me a cup of java, will ya?

224
00:24:07,430 --> 00:24:09,388
- Yeah?
<i>- Hello, Marlowe?</i>

225
00:24:09,516 --> 00:24:11,805
- Oh, hello, Bernie.
- No, it's me, Rigby.

226
00:24:11,935 --> 00:24:12,931
<i>What's up?</i>

227
00:24:13,061 --> 00:24:16,596
I'm on an important case. I need
your help. How soon can you get here?

228
00:24:16,731 --> 00:24:20,895
- I haven't had breakfast.
- Breakfast? You're late for lunch, pal.

229
00:24:21,026 --> 00:24:23,353
<i>- It's two o'clock.</i>
- Two o'clock?

230
00:24:23,488 --> 00:24:26,442
Hustle on over here.
I'll make you a cup of my famous java.

231
00:24:26,575 --> 00:24:30,193
- I'd rather buy my own.
- Suit yourself. See ya in a half-hour.

232
00:24:30,328 --> 00:24:33,282
And Marlowe. Wear a tie, for God's sake.

233
00:24:37,127 --> 00:24:39,250
What's that?

234
00:24:39,379 --> 00:24:41,418
I found it in Daddy's desk.

235
00:24:43,466 --> 00:24:47,546
It looks like a key to one of
those lockers at the train station.

236
00:24:47,679 --> 00:24:51,511
Number's been filed off.
What's it say on that envelope?

237
00:24:52,475 --> 00:24:54,717
"Most recent rat."

238
00:24:56,313 --> 00:24:59,479
- Very clever.
- You understand what it means?

239
00:24:59,608 --> 00:25:03,392
Just a hunch. You know the Chinese
have a different animal for every year?

240
00:25:03,528 --> 00:25:06,648
- Yes.
- Unless I miss my guess...

241
00:25:06,781 --> 00:25:09,866
...the most recent
Year of the Rat was 1936.

242
00:25:10,702 --> 00:25:13,656
This is the key to locker number 1936.

243
00:25:14,915 --> 00:25:17,869
- You're a very smart man.
- So was Abraham Lincoln.

244
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:21,500
Look what happened to him.
Smart can get you killed.

245
00:25:25,050 --> 00:25:27,292
I hope not.

246
00:25:28,595 --> 00:25:31,050
Sometimes I feel I would like to...

247
00:25:34,184 --> 00:25:36,675
<i>You'd like to what? Kiss me?</i>

248
00:25:37,354 --> 00:25:39,227
<i>Yeah, that would be nice.</i>

249
00:25:39,356 --> 00:25:43,603
<i>It would give me a chance to tell her
I was starting to feel something for her.</i>

250
00:25:43,735 --> 00:25:46,024
<i>Something warm and squishy.</i>

251
00:25:46,488 --> 00:25:51,648
<i>But a man in my business can't
take on a wife, have a bunch of kids.</i>

252
00:25:53,328 --> 00:25:56,448
- We wouldn't have to have kids.
- What?

253
00:25:59,793 --> 00:26:02,035
Look, this is getting us nowhere.

254
00:26:02,170 --> 00:26:03,795
But thanks anyway.

255
00:26:03,922 --> 00:26:07,836
You'd better go now. Marlowe's
coming over here to talk.

256
00:26:11,972 --> 00:26:14,260
If you need me, just call.

257
00:26:17,894 --> 00:26:20,266
You know how to dial, don't you?

258
00:26:20,397 --> 00:26:25,058
You just put your finger in the hole,
and make tiny little circles.

259
00:26:39,666 --> 00:26:41,955
Come on in. It's open.

260
00:26:46,255 --> 00:26:48,498
Hello, Marlowe.

261
00:26:48,633 --> 00:26:51,551
Dammit. You didn't do what I told ya.

262
00:26:52,095 --> 00:26:55,630
I hate that dumb way of wearing
your shirt buttoned with no tie.

263
00:26:55,765 --> 00:26:58,256
Let me get you a tie.

264
00:26:58,852 --> 00:27:02,684
Here. This one's blue,
but you can wear it with brown.

265
00:27:02,813 --> 00:27:05,483
- You annoy me.
- I annoy you?

266
00:27:05,609 --> 00:27:09,024
You come in here with no tie...
Are you drunk?

267
00:27:09,154 --> 00:27:11,941
- How many have you had?
- One martini.

268
00:27:12,073 --> 00:27:14,695
- I knew I was gonna see you.
- Sit down.

269
00:27:20,207 --> 00:27:22,780
Here's what I want you to do.

270
00:27:26,546 --> 00:27:30,129
Here's a list of names I found in a
bowl of soup. Don't ask me to explain.

271
00:27:30,258 --> 00:27:32,928
I think they're all dead.
I want you to check 'em out.

272
00:27:33,053 --> 00:27:36,552
And Marlowe? Put this on
for me, huh? As a favour.

273
00:27:36,681 --> 00:27:38,923
It's a clip-on.

274
00:27:42,395 --> 00:27:46,892
<i>I put Marlowe to work checking Kitty's
list against recent unsolved murders...</i>

275
00:27:47,025 --> 00:27:49,314
<i>...while I yellow-cabbed it
to the station...</i>

276
00:27:49,444 --> 00:27:53,276
<i>...to see how Dr Forrest's key
would fit into the puzzle.</i>

277
00:27:53,406 --> 00:27:56,740
<i>I sashayed over to locker number 1936.</i>

278
00:27:58,203 --> 00:28:02,034
<i>The key fit like a glove.
As I opened the locker...</i>

279
00:28:02,165 --> 00:28:05,747
<i>...I noticed a handsome guy
in a grey pinstripe watching me.</i>

280
00:28:05,877 --> 00:28:10,041
<i>It seemed I wasn't the only one who was
interested in the contents of that locker.</i>

281
00:28:10,465 --> 00:28:13,999
<i>Inside were two long lists of
Carlotta's friends and enemies.</i>

282
00:28:14,135 --> 00:28:16,805
<i>The first name that jumped out
was FX Huberman...</i>

283
00:28:16,930 --> 00:28:20,179
<i>...number 46 Bay Court Drive,
Grunion Point.</i>

284
00:28:21,268 --> 00:28:25,348
<i>I decided to take a little train ride
and visit Mr Huberman.</i>

285
00:28:26,022 --> 00:28:29,107
<i>I knew "Handsome" would follow me,
so to throw him off...</i>

286
00:28:29,234 --> 00:28:32,934
<i>...I cleverly ducked into
the men's room and lost him.</i>

287
00:28:33,822 --> 00:28:38,282
<i>There was no way he could follow me
unless I had toilet paper on my shoe.</i>

288
00:28:41,037 --> 00:28:43,077
Damn!

289
00:28:48,211 --> 00:28:51,082
<i>It wasn't really toilet paper,
it was a seat cover...</i>

290
00:28:51,214 --> 00:28:54,915
<i>...but it was enough for
a smart guy to make the connection.</i>

291
00:28:55,927 --> 00:28:57,883
<i>As soon as we went into a tunnel...</i>

292
00:28:58,013 --> 00:29:02,758
<i>...Handsome popped in and started
looking for a match... in my pockets.</i>

293
00:29:03,892 --> 00:29:07,512
Oh! Was that your leg?
- No, it was my face.

294
00:29:07,647 --> 00:29:09,854
I had no idea we were
going into a tunnel.

295
00:29:09,983 --> 00:29:12,225
I'm sure.

296
00:29:12,903 --> 00:29:14,942
I thought the compartment was empty.

297
00:29:15,071 --> 00:29:17,194
Yeah, right. Uh-huh, sure.

298
00:29:18,658 --> 00:29:22,573
- I'm so sorry. I hope I didn't hurt you.
- It's all right.

299
00:29:25,582 --> 00:29:28,073
To what do I owe
the pleasure of your company?

300
00:29:28,210 --> 00:29:31,543
The man in the next compartment's
smoking a vile cigar.

301
00:29:31,671 --> 00:29:34,956
I had to come in here.
You don't smoke, do you?

302
00:29:35,091 --> 00:29:38,258
- No, I have tuberculosis.
- Oh, thank heavens for that.

303
00:29:38,386 --> 00:29:41,471
After last night,
my head couldn't stand it.

304
00:29:45,810 --> 00:29:50,519
<i>I didn't want him to know where I was
going so I decided to put him away fast.</i>

305
00:29:52,275 --> 00:29:54,398
<i>I always carry my harmonica.</i>

306
00:29:54,527 --> 00:29:58,442
<i>It's lighter than an accordion,
and more powerful than a sleeping pill.</i>

307
00:30:05,247 --> 00:30:09,327
<i>I left him napping like a baby
when I ducked out at Grunion Point.</i>

308
00:30:14,130 --> 00:30:18,674
Here's three bucks if you can get
this cab to 46 Bay Court in ten minutes.

309
00:30:22,973 --> 00:30:25,428
Follow that cab!

310
00:30:27,769 --> 00:30:29,845
<i>It was a pretty clever thing I did.</i>

311
00:30:29,980 --> 00:30:34,725
<i>By taking the only two cabs, I made
sure Handsome couldn't follow me.</i>

312
00:30:36,860 --> 00:30:39,862
<i>When I arrived at Mr Huberman's,
I was surprised.</i>

313
00:30:39,989 --> 00:30:44,236
<i>Mr Huberman turned out to be
a sexy dame who was throwing a party.</i>

314
00:30:44,369 --> 00:30:48,663
<i>She didn't even ask me what I wanted,
just made me feel real welcome.</i>

315
00:30:53,253 --> 00:30:57,084
How about you, handsome?
Haven't I seen you somewhere before?

316
00:30:57,215 --> 00:30:59,753
Maybe. I've been somewhere before.

317
00:31:00,302 --> 00:31:04,086
It's nice of you to invite me.
I feel a little like a party crasher.

318
00:31:04,222 --> 00:31:06,630
I like party crashers.

319
00:31:06,766 --> 00:31:09,388
I like classy dames with bedroom eyes.

320
00:31:09,519 --> 00:31:11,559
You know something? I like you.

321
00:31:11,687 --> 00:31:13,562
I like me too.

322
00:31:13,689 --> 00:31:18,232
When these people leave, maybe...
you and I can have a party of our own.

323
00:31:18,361 --> 00:31:20,769
Oh, I... I have to think that over.

324
00:31:22,406 --> 00:31:23,687
<i>She was a fast thinker.</i>

325
00:31:24,284 --> 00:31:28,745
I'm very sorry. You all have to go.
It has been a perfectly hideous party.

326
00:31:30,290 --> 00:31:32,532
- Good night.
- Good night.

327
00:31:54,189 --> 00:31:56,643
Stuffy in here, isn't it?

328
00:31:58,568 --> 00:32:01,651
<i>Suddenly I realised
she'd slipped me a Mickey.</i>

329
00:32:01,780 --> 00:32:06,442
<i>My lips felt like two manhole covers.
My tongue felt like it had hair on it.</i>

330
00:32:06,576 --> 00:32:10,074
<i>My ears started to ring. I felt like a dog.</i>

331
00:32:12,749 --> 00:32:14,457
Woof!

332
00:32:14,584 --> 00:32:16,577
Woof, Huberman, woof!

333
00:32:16,711 --> 00:32:19,380
Come on. Let's go out dancin'.

334
00:32:20,381 --> 00:32:23,916
You put on your black dress,
and I'll go shave my tongue.

335
00:32:33,186 --> 00:32:35,808
# Barbasol, Barbasol

336
00:32:36,273 --> 00:32:38,312
# No brush, no lather, no rub-in

337
00:32:38,441 --> 00:32:40,149
# Wet your razor then begin

338
00:32:40,277 --> 00:32:43,692
# Barbasol, Barbasol

339
00:32:43,822 --> 00:32:46,360
# 0ompah, oompah, oompah, oompah

340
00:33:16,104 --> 00:33:17,729
Come on, FX. I'm ready!

341
00:33:19,232 --> 00:33:21,474
Let's go dancing.

342
00:33:34,956 --> 00:33:36,071
Hold it!

343
00:33:36,791 --> 00:33:39,247
Sorry, Dollface.

344
00:33:39,544 --> 00:33:43,245
<i>- How did you get here?</i>
- Your door was open, so I walked in.

345
00:33:44,174 --> 00:33:47,922
- I've been trying to call you all night.
- How did I get here?

346
00:33:48,052 --> 00:33:51,469
- I guess you must have crawled.
- Oh, God!

347
00:33:52,724 --> 00:33:55,262
- Oh, no, that's OK.
- It's just a little alcohol.

348
00:33:55,393 --> 00:33:57,351
- They don't hurt.
- Don't be a baby.

349
00:33:57,478 --> 00:33:59,886
Get back!

350
00:34:03,693 --> 00:34:06,065
What's up?

351
00:34:07,364 --> 00:34:09,984
Sam Hastings is dead.

352
00:34:10,116 --> 00:34:12,607
Poor rummy. How did he get it?

353
00:34:12,743 --> 00:34:16,112
Fell out of a window
reaching for a bottle of whisky.

354
00:34:16,248 --> 00:34:20,410
He could have been pushed. I'll have
Marlowe check his back for fingerprints.

355
00:34:20,544 --> 00:34:23,081
- Anything else?
- Yes.

356
00:34:23,213 --> 00:34:26,248
I found another note
Daddy wrote to himself.

357
00:34:26,383 --> 00:34:28,210
"NYTAG-216."

358
00:34:28,343 --> 00:34:31,214
I think it's a New York
licence plate number.

359
00:34:31,346 --> 00:34:34,715
Not bad, Dollface.
Unless I'm... Ohh! Agh!

360
00:34:34,849 --> 00:34:37,090
Careful. Let me get you some alcohol.

361
00:34:37,227 --> 00:34:39,266
No!

362
00:34:45,610 --> 00:34:48,481
It's not N-Y TAG. It's N-Y-T.

363
00:34:49,446 --> 00:34:51,689
<i>New York Times.</i>

364
00:34:57,414 --> 00:34:59,371
So what's "A-G"?

365
00:34:59,499 --> 00:35:03,413
- Standard library talk for August.
- And 216?

366
00:35:03,837 --> 00:35:07,537
Stands for the August 2nd issue,
page one, column six.

367
00:35:08,758 --> 00:35:11,000
Extension 20, please.

368
00:35:11,469 --> 00:35:13,628
Hi. It's me, Rigby.

369
00:35:13,763 --> 00:35:15,721
Sorry, Hot Legs, I've been busy.

370
00:35:15,849 --> 00:35:18,304
You sashay over to
<i>your New York Times file...</i>

371
00:35:18,434 --> 00:35:22,514
...read me what's on page one,
column six of the August 2nd issue...

372
00:35:22,647 --> 00:35:25,221
...maybe I'll wine and dine you
some night soon.

373
00:35:25,358 --> 00:35:26,390
I'll wait.

374
00:35:26,526 --> 00:35:28,934
You'd wine and dine her for information?

375
00:35:29,070 --> 00:35:31,443
Her? Him.

376
00:35:31,572 --> 00:35:34,242
Yeah... Then read me the whole article.

377
00:35:37,871 --> 00:35:40,113
<i>"Immer Essen".</i>

378
00:35:40,957 --> 00:35:43,329
Walter Neff's the owner.

379
00:35:44,336 --> 00:35:46,791
Thanks, Hot Legs. I owe you a big one.

380
00:35:47,421 --> 00:35:49,664
<i>Immer essen.</i>

381
00:35:52,594 --> 00:35:55,167
<i>Immer essen.</i>
That means "always eating".

382
00:35:55,388 --> 00:35:57,796
- What language?
- German.

383
00:35:58,475 --> 00:36:01,310
It's also the name of
a South American cruise ship.

384
00:36:01,436 --> 00:36:06,394
I know! When Sam Hastings
and my sister separated last July...

385
00:36:07,274 --> 00:36:09,683
...he took a South American tour
on that ship.

386
00:36:09,819 --> 00:36:11,941
Very interesting.

387
00:36:12,072 --> 00:36:15,571
Right after that tour,
the company cancelled its cruises.

388
00:36:15,699 --> 00:36:18,370
Now Sam Hastings is dead.

389
00:36:18,495 --> 00:36:23,038
- I don't see the connection.
- I don't either. That's what bothers me.

390
00:36:35,845 --> 00:36:38,087
Hello?

391
00:36:39,641 --> 00:36:41,514
- Who is it?
- This is Marlowe.

392
00:36:41,935 --> 00:36:45,553
Oh, hello, Mr Marlowe.
Would you hold a moment, please?

393
00:36:46,439 --> 00:36:48,895
- It's Marlowe.
- Good.

394
00:37:01,580 --> 00:37:06,324
Hello, Marlowe. Listen, don't check out
those unsolved murders right now.

395
00:37:06,459 --> 00:37:07,539
Yeah? Why not?

396
00:37:07,668 --> 00:37:12,580
I got something more important. You
ever had any dealings with Walter Neff?

397
00:37:12,716 --> 00:37:16,049
Walter Neff. He runs
a South American cruise-ship company.

398
00:37:17,094 --> 00:37:18,886
Good. Tell me about him.

399
00:37:19,055 --> 00:37:22,140
Cruises supermarkets
looking for blondes?

400
00:37:23,517 --> 00:37:26,436
Good. I'll supply the blonde.

401
00:37:31,693 --> 00:37:33,021
One other thing.

402
00:37:33,360 --> 00:37:37,062
If Walter Neff leaves the country,
I may have to take a little boat ride.

403
00:37:37,198 --> 00:37:42,193
If I do, stay off the booze. These
people we're dealing with are killers.

404
00:37:42,329 --> 00:37:45,910
<i>Well, thanks for telling me.</i>
Have a nice trip.

405
00:37:46,041 --> 00:37:49,492
I may not leave right away,
but thanks anyway. And Marlowe?

406
00:37:49,628 --> 00:37:51,953
<i>- You wearin' a tie?</i>
- Goodbye.

407
00:37:56,092 --> 00:37:58,630
<i>- What was that all about?</i>
- Marlowe knows Neff.

408
00:37:58,762 --> 00:38:01,632
Says he's a pushover
for beautiful blondes.

409
00:38:01,765 --> 00:38:04,137
It means we need a female spy.

410
00:38:09,314 --> 00:38:11,307
Why not use me?

411
00:38:16,154 --> 00:38:18,277
Sorry.

412
00:38:18,406 --> 00:38:20,779
You're not blonde enough.

413
00:38:33,588 --> 00:38:37,253
- I can always dye my hair.
- No dice, Dollface. You're a client.

414
00:38:37,384 --> 00:38:42,461
That's one thing I've learned about
clients. Dead ones don't pay their bills.

415
00:38:46,601 --> 00:38:48,890
Is that all you think of me?

416
00:38:49,020 --> 00:38:51,392
Someone who pays you $10 a day?

417
00:38:57,737 --> 00:39:01,189
That's right, Dollface.
To me you're just a meal ticket.

418
00:39:03,617 --> 00:39:05,907
<i>How could I tell her that I was lying?</i>

419
00:39:06,036 --> 00:39:10,035
<i>I'd work for nothing just to watch
her hair bounce as she walked...</i>

420
00:39:10,166 --> 00:39:13,915
<i>...smell her creamy skin,
cradle her head on my shoulder.</i>

421
00:39:14,588 --> 00:39:18,039
<i>Feel the slope of her waist,
the curve of her back...</i>

422
00:39:18,173 --> 00:39:21,259
<i>...and then gently caress
her two beautiful...</i>

423
00:39:26,890 --> 00:39:29,299
I'm sorry.

424
00:39:29,436 --> 00:39:32,556
I just don't like
being called a meal ticket.

425
00:39:47,829 --> 00:39:52,206
<i>As I started my search for a blonde spy,
I tried to get rid of the image of Juliet...</i>

426
00:39:52,334 --> 00:39:56,247
<i>...storming out of my office
with toothpaste on her shoes.</i>

427
00:39:57,964 --> 00:40:02,128
<i>First on my list was Monica Stillpond,
a bombshell who once told me...</i>

428
00:40:02,260 --> 00:40:06,803
<i>...she would do anything
for anybody anywhere at any time.</i>

429
00:40:09,016 --> 00:40:11,638
<i>But muscle gave me
my start in politics.</i>

430
00:40:11,770 --> 00:40:15,103
It was when I was assistant
to old man Zimmerman, the plumber.

431
00:40:15,232 --> 00:40:19,063
- Mr Madvig, you're joking.
- About the plumbing, or the muscle?

432
00:40:19,194 --> 00:40:21,732
I just can't imagine you as a plumber.

433
00:40:22,239 --> 00:40:24,564
<i>She was in the middle
of a fancy dinner party.</i>

434
00:40:24,699 --> 00:40:28,744
<i>But I couldn't waste time being polite.
I caught her attention.</i>

435
00:40:32,040 --> 00:40:35,741
Coffee will be served
in the living room, Mr Madvig.

436
00:40:36,962 --> 00:40:42,169
<i>One thing about Monica: The words
"I can't" weren't in her vocabulary.</i>

437
00:40:42,300 --> 00:40:44,791
Monica, I want you
to do something for me.

438
00:40:44,928 --> 00:40:47,004
I can't.

439
00:40:47,137 --> 00:40:50,921
<i>I guess she had added them
since the last time I'd seen her.</i>

440
00:40:52,310 --> 00:40:55,928
<i>The next one on my list was
Doris Devermont, an old flame of mine.</i>

441
00:40:56,064 --> 00:40:59,729
<i>With her I'd had the most honest
relationship I'd ever had with a woman.</i>

442
00:40:59,859 --> 00:41:04,438
<i>The only thing I'd lied about was my
name. I'd told her I was Teddy Novak...</i>

443
00:41:04,573 --> 00:41:08,072
<i>...so she couldn't track me down
if I got her pregnant.</i>

444
00:41:15,333 --> 00:41:17,456
<i>Doris remembered me, naturally.</i>

445
00:41:17,586 --> 00:41:19,543
How do you do, Mr Novak?

446
00:41:19,671 --> 00:41:24,914
Mr Novak? No hugs, no kisses? We used
to flop into each other's arms, Doris.

447
00:41:25,051 --> 00:41:29,095
Well, don't you think we really ought to
get to know each other all over again?

448
00:41:29,222 --> 00:41:33,801
It's only been five years. You were about
to serve me dinner when I had to leave.

449
00:41:33,935 --> 00:41:36,307
How stupid of me.
You must be famished.

450
00:41:36,438 --> 00:41:40,435
I should have thought of it sooner.
I'll get some coffee and sandwiches.

451
00:41:41,735 --> 00:41:44,142
<i>Coffee and sandwiches.</i>

452
00:41:44,279 --> 00:41:47,446
<i>Now I remembered Doris's
famous stale-bread sandwiches.</i>

453
00:41:48,325 --> 00:41:53,283
<i>She'd buy day-old bread, then toast it
