01:01:49,985 --> 01:01:53,104
<i>I spoke to Victor.
He'll give me the divorce.</i>

682
01:01:53,237 --> 01:01:56,773
<i>I'll tell you what. Come down
tomorrow. We'll drive back together.</i>

683
01:01:56,908 --> 01:02:01,902
<i>Wonderful! I can't wait to
come bouncing back into your life again.</i>

684
01:02:05,541 --> 01:02:08,163
No dice, Margaret.
Call me in another 12 years.

685
01:02:08,295 --> 01:02:10,536
All right, darling.

686
01:02:47,000 --> 01:02:48,992
- Hello?
<i>- Mr Reardon...</i>

687
01:02:49,127 --> 01:02:52,081
<i>...I have decided to close this case
as of this moment.</i>

688
01:02:52,212 --> 01:02:55,581
A cheque will be in the mail
for you tomorrow.

689
01:02:55,717 --> 01:02:59,465
Please do not try to contact me
as I will be out of town for some time.

690
01:02:59,971 --> 01:03:02,842
Juliet, has someone
got a gun to your head?

691
01:03:03,683 --> 01:03:05,142
Juliet!

692
01:03:09,188 --> 01:03:11,514
<i>A half-bottle of bourbon later
I still couldn't believe it.</i>

693
01:03:11,649 --> 01:03:13,856
<i>Was Juliet crazy like her sister?</i>

694
01:03:13,985 --> 01:03:18,398
<i>Had she fallen in love with the cab
driver on the way to the drugstore?</i>

695
01:03:18,531 --> 01:03:22,612
<i>Or was she a member of the Carlotta
conspiracy and had set me up?</i>

696
01:03:22,744 --> 01:03:26,112
<i>Finally, I arrived at
a very important conclusion.</i>

697
01:03:26,789 --> 01:03:29,032
Shit on her!

698
01:03:41,930 --> 01:03:44,385
All dames are alike.

699
01:03:45,934 --> 01:03:49,432
They reach down your throat,
grab your heart... and pull it out.

700
01:03:49,563 --> 01:03:54,224
They throw it on the floor... and
they step on it with their high heels.

701
01:03:54,900 --> 01:03:59,028
They spit on it, shove it in the oven,
then cook the shit out of it.

702
01:04:00,614 --> 01:04:03,782
They slice it into little pieces,
slam it on a hunk of toast...

703
01:04:03,909 --> 01:04:06,366
...and they serve it to ya.

704
01:04:06,496 --> 01:04:10,197
They expect you to say
"Thanks, honey, it's delicious."

705
01:04:13,086 --> 01:04:16,289
Well, it's not delicious, Juliet Forrest.

706
01:04:16,423 --> 01:04:18,664
It's rotten.

707
01:04:19,174 --> 01:04:21,749
I don't give a damn
if I ever hear from you again.

708
01:04:28,017 --> 01:04:29,677
- Juliet?
- This is Alan.

709
01:04:29,811 --> 01:04:31,934
Alan?

710
01:04:32,605 --> 01:04:36,520
- Come on, Marlowe, no games.
- I never could fool you, could I?

711
01:04:37,944 --> 01:04:40,020
No.

712
01:04:40,154 --> 01:04:42,064
Listen, Marlowe.

713
01:04:42,490 --> 01:04:44,863
Juliet left me, and...

714
01:04:46,035 --> 01:04:48,787
...I feel like I've been hit
with a wet frying pan.

715
01:04:48,914 --> 01:04:50,990
How the hell do you pick up the pieces?

716
01:04:51,124 --> 01:04:55,073
I'm beginning to realise it's better
to have something to look forward to.

717
01:04:55,212 --> 01:04:58,166
"Look forward to." Like what? Work?

718
01:04:58,297 --> 01:05:00,207
I can't get a break on this case.

719
01:05:00,342 --> 01:05:02,962
I don't even know who the hell
this Carlotta dame is.

720
01:05:03,094 --> 01:05:05,549
<i>Can you get a map of South America?</i>

721
01:05:05,680 --> 01:05:08,254
- Yeah. You got something?
- Look up Peru.

722
01:05:12,687 --> 01:05:13,553
Got it!

723
01:05:13,688 --> 01:05:16,559
There's a little town
on the coast called Paita.

724
01:05:16,691 --> 01:05:19,099
<i>Tell me where it is.</i>

725
01:05:21,196 --> 01:05:24,279
It's right next to
a tiny little island called...

726
01:05:24,406 --> 01:05:27,611
You son of a gun! Carlotta!

727
01:05:28,745 --> 01:05:31,116
Damn! It's not a woman's name.

728
01:05:32,040 --> 01:05:34,448
It's a place.

729
01:05:34,583 --> 01:05:37,206
- Thanks, Marlowe. I owe ya.
- Good.

730
01:05:37,337 --> 01:05:40,338
I'm leaving for Carlotta right now.

731
01:05:40,465 --> 01:05:43,799
Even if Juliet's gone,
I'm gonna solve this case...

732
01:05:43,927 --> 01:05:48,007
...no matter how many killers are
involved, even if Juliet's one of 'em.

733
01:05:48,138 --> 01:05:50,809
Any idea where in Carlotta
I should start looking?

734
01:05:50,934 --> 01:05:53,555
<i>There's a little café right on the bay.</i>

735
01:05:54,938 --> 01:06:00,063
<i>When I arrived, I thought of the words
Marlowe had said to me 15 years ago:</i>

736
01:06:01,069 --> 01:06:03,394
<i>"Dead men don't wear plaid."</i>

737
01:06:05,907 --> 01:06:08,232
<i>Dead men don't wear plaid.</i>

738
01:06:09,578 --> 01:06:12,198
<i>I still don't know what it means.</i>

739
01:06:13,290 --> 01:06:17,369
<i>Carlotta was the kind of town where
they spell trouble t-r-u-b-i-l...</i>

740
01:06:17,502 --> 01:06:20,787
<i>...and if you try to
correct them, they kill you.</i>

741
01:06:35,729 --> 01:06:37,805
<i>I knew Marlowe had steered me right.</i>

742
01:06:37,939 --> 01:06:41,770
<i>There was Kitty Collins, the girl
who ditched me in Santa Barbara.</i>

743
01:06:44,070 --> 01:06:46,396
Señor Reardon.

744
01:06:51,660 --> 01:06:53,902
Manuel Alesandro.

745
01:06:57,334 --> 01:06:59,243
Not quite.

746
01:06:59,376 --> 01:07:01,335
Carlos Rodriguez.

747
01:07:03,757 --> 01:07:05,666
- Carlos Rodriguez?
<i>- Sí.</i>

748
01:07:06,051 --> 01:07:10,428
Before the war...
we ran guns to the rebels.

749
01:07:12,097 --> 01:07:13,925
Oh, yeah.

750
01:07:14,559 --> 01:07:16,467
You're a cop.

751
01:07:16,603 --> 01:07:18,512
<i>Sí, sí, sí.</i>

752
01:07:18,646 --> 01:07:20,972
I have joined the establishment.

753
01:07:22,484 --> 01:07:27,395
That's good, Carlos. I'm here on an
investigation. Maybe you can help me.

754
01:07:27,529 --> 01:07:30,068
There is much to investigate in Carlotta.

755
01:07:30,867 --> 01:07:33,572
The whole island is like a powder keg.

756
01:07:33,703 --> 01:07:37,914
There is much tension, the...
the smell of something rotten.

757
01:07:39,125 --> 01:07:43,039
That's what I'm here for.
To find out what it is that smells.

758
01:07:43,171 --> 01:07:44,748
Psst!

759
01:07:44,881 --> 01:07:49,258
Be careful of the, uh,
fat one who sweats a lot.

760
01:07:51,804 --> 01:07:53,180
What about Kitty Collins?

761
01:07:53,306 --> 01:07:56,639
She doesn't sweat as much,
but she's just as dangerous.

762
01:07:56,767 --> 01:07:59,140
# What you want

763
01:07:59,271 --> 01:08:01,309
# Everybody wants

764
01:08:05,651 --> 01:08:08,108
They say she is one of them.

765
01:08:08,904 --> 01:08:11,313
Who is..."them"?

766
01:08:11,992 --> 01:08:15,491
Nobody knows.
Only they know who is "them".

767
01:08:16,371 --> 01:08:20,120
But there is a man.
<i>His name is Arroz. Rice.</i>

768
01:08:21,792 --> 01:08:24,283
Kitty Collins is in love with him.

769
01:08:25,045 --> 01:08:27,372
He is a killer.

770
01:08:27,506 --> 01:08:29,796
Rice, huh?

771
01:08:30,594 --> 01:08:33,085
- Thanks, Carlos.
<i>- De nada, señor.</i>

772
01:08:35,223 --> 01:08:38,259
- Where are you staying?
- Hotel Guano.

773
01:08:38,393 --> 01:08:41,228
Ha! I'll be in touch.

774
01:08:41,353 --> 01:08:43,810
<i>Cuidado, Señor Reardon.</i>

775
01:08:43,940 --> 01:08:47,523
<i>Cuidado, Carlos... <i>Cuidado. </i></i>

776
01:08:47,652 --> 01:08:51,103
<i>I wanted Kitty Collins
to tell "them" I was in town...</i>

777
01:08:51,239 --> 01:08:54,572
<i>...so I tossed a five-pesetaria coin
into the bowl.</i>

778
01:08:54,826 --> 01:08:57,827
<i>The clank was loud enough
to make her look my way.</i>

779
01:08:58,162 --> 01:09:02,326
<i>That five-pesetaria coin was
the best investment I ever made.</i>

780
01:09:02,458 --> 01:09:07,619
<i>The next day, I hooked a big fish:
A fat one who sweats a lot.</i>

781
01:09:10,133 --> 01:09:13,882
<i>- Señor?</i>
- Nothing alcoholic. Oh, a beer, maybe.

782
01:09:14,346 --> 01:09:16,006
<i>Sí, señor.</i>

783
01:09:16,889 --> 01:09:19,345
Hard liquor goes to my feet.

784
01:09:22,019 --> 01:09:25,104
Just a minute, Mr Rigby.

785
01:09:25,982 --> 01:09:28,520
We know who you are, Mr Rigby.

786
01:09:28,652 --> 01:09:30,609
I'm interested. Who am I?

787
01:09:30,736 --> 01:09:34,023
You could be a guy
who collects $10,000...

788
01:09:34,699 --> 01:09:36,858
...just to leave this stinkin' town.

789
01:09:36,993 --> 01:09:39,663
- I could, could I?
- You know who I could be?

790
01:09:41,706 --> 01:09:43,913
Hunchback of Notre Dame?

791
01:09:44,041 --> 01:09:48,537
I could be the guy
who hands ya... them $10,000.

792
01:09:49,463 --> 01:09:53,081
$10,000. Me to you... just like that.

793
01:09:53,218 --> 01:09:57,465
Sorry. My price for leaving
stinking towns is 11,500...

794
01:09:57,596 --> 01:10:00,383
...and a kiss on the lips
from Carmen Miranda.

795
01:10:00,517 --> 01:10:04,384
Pass it on to "them". Room 204.

796
01:10:05,605 --> 01:10:07,313
Room 204, señora.

797
01:10:17,449 --> 01:10:19,277
Come in.

798
01:10:21,120 --> 01:10:24,121
Right on time, Kitty. Been expecting ya.

799
01:10:24,249 --> 01:10:26,490
Thought you'd come last night.

800
01:10:26,626 --> 01:10:29,746
- I wasn't thinking too well last night.
- Keep talking.

801
01:10:29,880 --> 01:10:32,714
You see, I just
found out something, Rigby.

802
01:10:33,592 --> 01:10:37,589
Who you are, what you do,
and why you're in Carlotta.

803
01:10:37,720 --> 01:10:40,176
I'm here to bust up your game.

804
01:10:43,226 --> 01:10:48,053
I don't get it. A class girl like you
in love with a killer like Rice.

805
01:10:48,189 --> 01:10:50,810
Who... what... why?

806
01:10:50,942 --> 01:10:52,982
When you love someone...

807
01:10:53,110 --> 01:10:57,357
...I guess it doesn't make
any difference who, what or why.

808
01:10:57,490 --> 01:10:59,945
You go right on loving them.

809
01:11:02,078 --> 01:11:04,319
Yeah, you do, don't ya?

810
01:11:05,207 --> 01:11:07,661
I feel as if...

811
01:11:12,254 --> 01:11:15,126
Make me another drink, will you, baby?

812
01:11:19,845 --> 01:11:21,802
Hello?

813
01:11:21,932 --> 01:11:24,423
<i>- What's up, amigo?</i>
- Plenty.

814
01:11:25,100 --> 01:11:28,435
A plane arrived today, and
all the passengers spoke German.

815
01:11:28,562 --> 01:11:32,014
- German?
<i>- Mm-hm. Our friend Rice was there.</i>

816
01:11:32,150 --> 01:11:35,233
They gave him a packet.
It was marked today's date...

817
01:11:35,362 --> 01:11:37,899
...and "Final Instructions".
- How do you know?

818
01:11:38,031 --> 01:11:42,942
I was hired to protect Rice until he
gets on that plane with Kitty Collins...

819
01:11:43,078 --> 01:11:45,651
<i>...tonight after the Carlotta Festival.</i>

820
01:11:46,706 --> 01:11:48,533
<i>Why are you telling me this?</i>

821
01:11:48,666 --> 01:11:51,620
Because the lives of
millions of innocent p...

822
01:11:51,753 --> 01:11:54,125
Carlos? Carlos!

823
01:11:55,256 --> 01:11:57,296
Carlos!

824
01:11:57,425 --> 01:11:59,465
Damn.

825
01:12:06,476 --> 01:12:08,883
Where are you and Rice headed tonight?

826
01:12:09,271 --> 01:12:12,141
What do you know about
a plane with Germermans on it?

827
01:12:12,274 --> 01:12:14,313
Germerm... Germans.

828
01:12:15,193 --> 01:12:17,233
Germermans.

829
01:12:18,196 --> 01:12:21,565
There's a plane with mermans on it.

830
01:12:23,410 --> 01:12:25,734
The plane's in town.

831
01:12:27,038 --> 01:12:29,279
Ethel Merman came in on it.

832
01:12:35,338 --> 01:12:37,875
Wanna go see Ethel Merman with me?

833
01:12:39,426 --> 01:12:41,668
I'll buy two tickets.

834
01:12:41,802 --> 01:12:45,137
Let me get on my pyjamas,
I'll be ready to go.

835
01:12:46,850 --> 01:12:49,007
<i>I'd done some brilliant things
in my time.</i>

836
01:12:49,144 --> 01:12:53,058
<i>Asking Kitty Collins to mix me
a drink wasn't one of them.</i>

837
01:12:54,733 --> 01:12:58,813
<i>When I came to, I could make out
only light and shadow at first.</i>

838
01:12:58,944 --> 01:13:02,231
<i>Then I saw an unfamiliar face.
But even in my stupor...</i>

839
01:13:02,364 --> 01:13:06,529
<i>...I knew he was one of the big fish
in the conspiracy: Rice!</i>

840
01:13:06,660 --> 01:13:08,950
Well, I believe
that about winds things up.

841
01:13:09,456 --> 01:13:13,121
<i>- I'm gonna wind you up on a rope.</i>
- But you're the one who's gonna die.

842
01:13:13,251 --> 01:13:18,162
Better make it look good. If anything
fishy happens to me, the FBI...

843
01:13:18,298 --> 01:13:19,840
It'll look very natural.

844
01:13:19,966 --> 01:13:24,129
People who know Rigby Reardon
know I'd never die a natural death.

845
01:13:26,180 --> 01:13:28,387
Do you think
I'd leave you around to talk?!

846
01:13:28,516 --> 01:13:30,722
You've already talked too much!

847
01:13:37,984 --> 01:13:40,060
Hold it, Rice!

848
01:13:40,570 --> 01:13:43,939
You're not getting on that plane
tonight. I want those papers.

849
01:13:44,074 --> 01:13:47,157
I'm gonna walk out of this room.
You won't shoot.

850
01:13:47,285 --> 01:13:49,526
I won't?

851
01:13:50,539 --> 01:13:54,999
That was a warning shot, Rice. And I
don't fire as many of 'em as I used to.

852
01:14:08,431 --> 01:14:10,553
<i>Rigby! Señor!</i>

853
01:14:10,684 --> 01:14:12,722
- I heard shots.
- I'm all right.

854
01:14:12,852 --> 01:14:15,140
- Rice went that way.
- Come on, Carlos!

855
01:14:15,272 --> 01:14:19,104
Are you wearing pyjamas?
<i>Señor, I'll help you take them off.</i>

856
01:14:20,734 --> 01:14:23,440
I don't need help
with my pyjamas! Stop!

857
01:14:23,572 --> 01:14:25,444
<i>- Sí.</i>
- Carlos!

858
01:14:25,572 --> 01:14:30,033
<i>Sí. Don't worry about your pyjamas,</i>
<i>señor. I'll take care of them.</i>

859
01:14:30,160 --> 01:14:33,328
Out of the way!
We are chasing a killer!

860
01:14:33,455 --> 01:14:35,912
Everybody stand back! He's with me.

861
01:14:37,961 --> 01:14:40,084
Coming through!

862
01:14:41,880 --> 01:14:43,625
<i>Señor!</i>

863
01:14:43,757 --> 01:14:45,798
<i>Cuidado, señor. Cuidado!</i>

864
01:14:47,053 --> 01:14:49,722
- Stand back!
<i>- Cuidado!</i>

865
01:14:51,349 --> 01:14:53,507
<i>Señor! Your pyjamas!</i>

866
01:14:53,643 --> 01:14:56,216
Forget the pyjamas!

867
01:14:59,440 --> 01:15:01,516
- Are you all right?
- It's just a bullet.

868
01:15:01,651 --> 01:15:05,151
My wife Carmelita
<i>will suck it out. Go ahead, señor.</i>

869
01:15:05,906 --> 01:15:10,116
And don't worry about your pyjamas.
I'll take care of them!

870
01:15:58,333 --> 01:16:00,575
"Final Instructions".

871
01:16:06,800 --> 01:16:09,421
So that's their game.

872
01:16:18,394 --> 01:16:20,635
"Rasmussen Place".

873
01:16:41,418 --> 01:16:45,665
<i>The last thing I expected to see
was Juliet and her father, alive...</i>

874
01:16:45,796 --> 01:16:49,794
<i>...talking with their butler,
who was dressed in a Nazi uniform.</i>

875
01:16:49,926 --> 01:16:52,463
<i>Yeah. That explained a lot.</i>

876
01:16:52,596 --> 01:16:56,011
<i>Why Juliet was able
to translate German, for one thing.</i>

877
01:16:56,141 --> 01:16:58,430
<i>I'd been played for a sucker.</i>

878
01:16:58,560 --> 01:17:01,643
<i>But it wasn't too late
to set things straight.</i>

879
01:17:06,902 --> 01:17:08,774
Yaaah!

880
01:17:11,113 --> 01:17:13,985
OK, hands in the air.
Over on the steps. Let's go!

881
01:17:14,117 --> 01:17:17,949
It's time for a class picture.
Tall ones in back, short ones in front.

882
01:17:18,245 --> 01:17:20,702
Now sit! Hold hands.

883
01:17:21,916 --> 01:17:24,157
Now smile.

884
01:17:24,628 --> 01:17:26,037
- That's nice.
- Rigby...

885
01:17:26,171 --> 01:17:29,455
Hold it! Stay where you are,
you dirty, lying Nazi scum.

886
01:17:29,591 --> 01:17:30,870
Rigby!

887
01:17:31,009 --> 01:17:34,259
I should have known. I fell for
a dame who played me for a sucker.

888
01:17:34,386 --> 01:17:36,925
No, Mr Reardon. She did not
play you for a sucker.

889
01:17:37,056 --> 01:17:43,011
<i>I did. Pretending to be a butler, waiting
on inferior races was galling to me.</i>

890
01:17:43,146 --> 01:17:47,190
- But I fooled everyone.
- You see, Rigby? I didn't betray you.

891
01:17:47,317 --> 01:17:50,353
- How did you know to come here?
- Marlowe told me.

892
01:17:50,486 --> 01:17:53,571
That's how I found Daddy.
I smelled his cheese moulds.

893
01:17:53,698 --> 01:17:56,070
I am sorry to interrupt
such a tender scene...

894
01:17:56,200 --> 01:17:58,656
...but we have a plan to carry out now.

895
01:17:59,037 --> 01:18:03,117
- Who are you really, kraut?
- Field Marshal Wilfred von Kluck.

896
01:18:03,250 --> 01:18:05,621
- At your service.
- Von Kluck?

897
01:18:05,751 --> 01:18:08,670
Former chief of Hitler's
Special Secret Weapons Corps.

898
01:18:08,796 --> 01:18:11,335
I'm flattered. How did you know?

899
01:18:11,465 --> 01:18:13,922
I figured out
your whole stinking scheme.

900
01:18:14,051 --> 01:18:17,966
How you duped Dr Forrest into helping
you. How you flew in your agents!

901
01:18:18,098 --> 01:18:20,968
The finest officers in the Führer's army.

902
01:18:21,560 --> 01:18:25,094
- Former army.
- For the moment.

903
01:18:25,230 --> 01:18:27,138
But we shall rise again.

904
01:18:27,274 --> 01:18:30,310
- We'll see about that.
- How did they use Daddy?

905
01:18:30,443 --> 01:18:34,192
Bullet-head here found out your father
had developed a cheese mould...

906
01:18:34,321 --> 01:18:37,856
...so powerful it could decompose
rocks, trees and mountains.

907
01:18:37,993 --> 01:18:41,196
He devised a plan to dissolve
the entire United States.

908
01:18:41,328 --> 01:18:44,615
At first your father gave
this swine information because...

909
01:18:44,748 --> 01:18:48,413
Please, Mr Reardon.
<i>Allow me to tell the story.</i>

910
01:18:48,877 --> 01:18:51,119
- Your father went along...
- Mr Reardon.

911
01:18:51,256 --> 01:18:55,752
It is customary in these situations for
the developer of the plan to describe it.

912
01:18:55,884 --> 01:19:00,961
I beg your pardon. It's customary for the
private eye to tell how he figured it out.

913
01:19:01,099 --> 01:19:02,926
No, it is my right!

914
01:19:03,058 --> 01:19:06,843
We were able to dupe Dr Forrest by
posing as a humanitarian organisation...

915
01:19:06,980 --> 01:19:10,230
...who planned to wipe out hunger
by ageing cheese faster.

916
01:19:10,358 --> 01:19:14,486
- When he saw what they were doing...
- He assembled lists of our agents...

917
01:19:14,612 --> 01:19:19,440
- And seemed about to go to the FBI...
- We had to drug him and bring him...

918
01:19:19,575 --> 01:19:22,660
Here, faking his death
so there'd be no investigation...

919
01:19:22,787 --> 01:19:25,823
But while testing the mould
on a small island nearby...

920
01:19:25,957 --> 01:19:30,001
<i>The Immer Essen passed by. Some of</i>
the passengers saw the island dissolve...

921
01:19:30,128 --> 01:19:32,797
They were therefore labelled "enemies".

922
01:19:32,923 --> 01:19:35,378
We had Neff cancel
all further tours, and our...

923
01:19:35,508 --> 01:19:39,719
...friends systematically began to
eliminate everyone on that cruise ship!

924
01:19:39,846 --> 01:19:42,302
<i>- Schweinehund!</i>
- Jerk!

925
01:19:44,935 --> 01:19:46,677
Now...

926
01:19:47,687 --> 01:19:50,724
...we are ready.
Our agents have just returned...

927
01:19:50,856 --> 01:19:53,775
...after planting cheese bombs
throughout America.

928
01:19:53,902 --> 01:19:57,352
With America destroyed,
we will win the next war.

929
01:19:57,489 --> 01:19:59,197
And the one after that, too!

930
01:19:59,323 --> 01:20:03,652
When these switches are thrown, your
meddling country will disintegrate...

931
01:20:03,787 --> 01:20:05,778
...like a mouldy hunk of Liederkranz!

932
01:20:05,914 --> 01:20:09,198
Hold the mould, Kluck. Those switches
aren't going to be thrown.

933
01:20:09,334 --> 01:20:13,118
<i>Und I think they will be.</i>

934
01:20:13,255 --> 01:20:15,294
<i>Halt ihn!</i>

935
01:20:18,677 --> 01:20:21,677
Good... good.

936
01:20:23,138 --> 01:20:26,722
I'm sorry to prevent
your becoming a hero, Herr Reardon.

937
01:20:26,850 --> 01:20:30,303
Actually, it is too bad
you and I are on opposite sides.

938
01:20:30,605 --> 01:20:34,140
I admire your tenacity.
Under different circumstances...

939
01:20:34,275 --> 01:20:39,732
...I might have even allowed you to live,
perhaps as my, uh... valet, or butler.

940
01:20:40,864 --> 01:20:44,151
And what would you have me
become, Herr Field Marshal?

941
01:20:44,285 --> 01:20:46,077
- What?
- I said...

942
01:20:46,204 --> 01:20:50,367
...what position could I hold
in your "New Order"?

943
01:20:50,500 --> 01:20:53,703
Juliet! What are you saying?
He's a Nazi! Don't beg a Nazi!

944
01:20:53,836 --> 01:20:56,410
<i>Would I be your... Reinemachefrau?</i>

945
01:20:56,547 --> 01:20:59,715
<i>Ja, you could, uh... you could be that.</i>

946
01:20:59,842 --> 01:21:02,760
- What is that? What is it?!
- Tell him.

947
01:21:02,888 --> 01:21:05,757
<i>- Reinemachefrau.
- Rrrreinemachefrau.</i>

948
01:21:07,475 --> 01:21:11,972
It means she could be
my... cleaning woman.

949
01:21:12,355 --> 01:21:14,562
Cleaning woman!

950
01:21:24,618 --> 01:21:26,859
All right, join your pals.
Let's go! Move it!

951
01:21:26,994 --> 01:21:30,364
Great work, Juliet.
Go find Carlos Rodriguez for me.

952
01:21:30,498 --> 01:21:31,827
All right.

953
01:21:31,957 --> 01:21:34,995
Your having that gun
won't stop us, Herr Reardon.

954
01:21:35,127 --> 01:21:38,745
We are a dedicated people,
willing to sacrifice ourselves!

955
01:21:38,882 --> 01:21:42,666
There are only six bullets
in that gun. There are nine of us.

956
01:21:42,801 --> 01:21:46,633
Thus at least three will survive
to throw those switches.

957
01:21:46,765 --> 01:21:49,766
OK. But who's going to win the lottery...

958
01:21:49,893 --> 01:21:52,465
...and who's going to lose?

959
01:21:54,731 --> 01:21:58,064
Cowards! Fools!

960
01:21:58,902 --> 01:22:00,940
I'll do it myself!

961
01:22:01,070 --> 01:22:02,730
Sorry, pal. You're through.

962
01:22:08,870 --> 01:22:11,538
Not... quite.

963
01:22:15,877 --> 01:22:17,916
At least... we got...

964
01:22:18,588 --> 01:22:22,799
...Terre Haute, India... na.

965
01:22:24,052 --> 01:22:27,338
Damn! They were just about
to get a public library.

966
01:22:28,139 --> 01:22:30,215
Carlos, lock these creeps up.

967
01:22:30,349 --> 01:22:32,259
With pleasure!

968
01:22:32,393 --> 01:22:35,727
<i>0K, creeps. Vámonos! Let's go!</i>

969
01:22:36,647 --> 01:22:38,806
<i>Schweinehunds! Pig dogs!</i>

970
01:22:39,276 --> 01:22:43,404
I pity the Devil the day
you boys start arriving in bunches.

971
01:22:47,033 --> 01:22:50,237
<i>Señor Reardon, when will</i>
you be leaving Carlotta?

972
01:22:51,121 --> 01:22:53,159
- Next plane out, Carlos.
- Aha!

973
01:22:53,290 --> 01:22:56,989
That gives me four hours
to wash and press your pyjamas.

974
01:22:57,626 --> 01:22:59,667
No, thanks, Carlos.

975
01:23:00,337 --> 01:23:03,008
I don't think I'll be
needing my pyjamas any more.

976
01:23:09,139 --> 01:23:11,381
What a guy!

977
01:23:24,653 --> 01:23:26,481
What are you... doing?

978
01:23:26,614 --> 01:23:28,524
Adjusting your willie.

979
01:23:28,658 --> 01:23:32,703
When you fell through the window,
it shifted out of whack.

980
01:23:32,829 --> 01:23:35,154
- Thanks.
- You're welcome.

981
01:23:36,749 --> 01:23:40,450
<i>I hadn't had my willie
adjusted like that in a long time...</i>

982
01:23:41,129 --> 01:23:43,750
<i>...especially without having to beg.</i>

983
01:23:44,632 --> 01:23:47,206
<i>So there it was - the Carlotta mystery...</i>

984
01:23:47,343 --> 01:23:50,048
<i>...all wrapped up in a neat little bundle.</i>

985
01:23:50,513 --> 01:23:54,511
<i>As I stood there kissing Juliet, I thought
of nothing but hanging up my gun...</i>

986
01:23:54,643 --> 01:23:58,475
<i>...and spending the rest of my days
in that ivy-covered cottage.</i>

987
01:23:58,604 --> 01:24:01,605
<i>Little did I realise
that less than a year later...</i>

988
01:24:01,732 --> 01:24:04,817
<i>...she and I would have
an even more exciting adventure...</i>

989
01:24:04,945 --> 01:24:08,147
<i>...which is coming soon
to your neighbourhood theatre...</i>

990
01:24:08,281 --> 01:24:10,951
<i>...with a possible nude scene by Juliet.</i>


